post_text:
OHS varsity field hockey picked up its first win of the season, beating Summit Country Day 4-2 on the road Sept. 10.

Junior forward Mallory Moran pulled off the first "hat-trick" of her career, leading the scoring for OHS. Sophomore Allyssa Nelson-Mays was credited with an assist on one of Moran's goals and added one of her own.

Senior Goalkeeper Mikey Martindale had eight saves, with senior defender Allie Hall and junior defender Amelia Tuttle adding goal saving "stick saves” for OHS.

Next up, OHS welcomes local rival Fairmont to Lane Stadium Wednesday, Sept. 16 at 5:00 p.m.

post_text:
All of the bathrooms at Smith Elementary are now open this week after a second round of testing came back negative for legionella bacteria.

Trace amounts of the bacteria had been found in one girls’ restroom on the second floor in August after being closed in March due to the state-wide school closure and construction that took place during the summer as part of the District’s Phase 1 Master Facilities Plan. Following the initial test results, the District followed the recommendations of Solid Blend Technologies to flush that portion of the Smith Elementary water system and then retest.

Oakwood Schools conducted proactive testing in all of its facilities during the summer in preparation to reopen the school buildings. All of the District’s other initial test results came back negative for the bacteria. Due to the bathroom being closed since March, experts say there is no reason to believe anyone was exposed to the bacteria.

Oakwood Junior High boys’ and girls’ cross country teams came away with two second place finishes in the Bob Schul Invitational at Milton Union Saturday, Aug. 29.

For the girls, seventh grader Addy Kash was the top runner, finishing in 9th place with a time of 14:32. Along with Kash, Delaney Cahill, Lily Rich, Sarah Redden and Riley Meador combined for the team points. OJH finished just behind Monroe, the girls’ champions. Waynesville finished third.

On the boys’ side, Nico Ferra was the top runner for OJH, finishing fifth with a time of 12:17. In addition to Ferra, Matthew Walton, Kellen Hart, Robert Einhorn and Liam Cantrell combined for the team points. OJH finished second to Bellbrook. Waynesvile was third.

Tech Tip: Be on the lookout for "spear phishing."

Spear Phishing: The fraudulent practice of sending emails ostensibly from a known or trusted sender in order to induce targeted individuals to reveal confidential information.

The technique has been around for a while, but it seems to be getting more common, thus the warning.

A spear phisher will often pose as an authority figure and ask for money to be transferred or for sensitive information to be given to them. They'll often disguise the email address to look like it originated from the authority figure and ask/demand that it be done quickly.

Example: You receive an email from Dr. Ramey. The email even seems to have come from his…

Dear Oakwood Families,

It was an excellent day for our students and our staff. The kids who returned to the buildings were great and staff members were ecstatic to see them back in their classes. I talked with several parents and students throughout the day and they were appreciative to be back and said how happy they were with how the day had gone.

The protocols we have been working on this summer were successful. We did experience a minor glitch at the start of the day as kids bunched up at the door anxious to get inside. But isn’t that a great thing to hear, our kids were excited to get into school! By the afternoon session, it was better and tomorrow will be better still as students…

post_text:
Wright Memorial Library is hosting Let's Talk Race for Teens Wednesday, July 22 at 7 p.m.

The online event will use the Conversation Cafe model to talk about issues regarding race and human diversity.

Topics to be addressed are how to effectively speak up when you hear a racist remark or joke, what it means to be the race that you are, and how your education has affected your understanding of racial issues. We will break into small groups with a leader designated for each group.

All participants agree to be open-minded, accepting, curious, discovery-oriented, sincere, and respectful. Grades 7-12.

If you're interested, registration is required. Visit the library's website at https://www.wrightlibrary.org/letstalkteen

Welcome to Work Wednesday, a weekly update of the Oakwood Schools Master Facilities Plan Phase 1 work this summer.

For more, check out our website at https://www.oakwoodschools.org/mfp/new-mfp
text:
Welcome to Work Wednesday, a weekly update of the Oakwood Schools Master Facilities Plan Phase 1 work this summer.

For more, check out our website at https://www.oakwoodschools.org/mfp/new-mfp

post_text:
Phase 1 of the Oakwood Schools Master Facilities Plan is underway at four of the District’s five buildings.

Crews have begun replacing the slate roof on OHS, which was built in 1924. New slate tiles along with components of the gutter and downspout system will be replaced to prevent leaking in the nearly 100-year-old building, while ensuring the architectural integrity of the building and the community. Other high quality materials will be used on the roof in less-visible areas.

Other summer projects at OJH/OHS include installing a new HVAC system, remodeling bathrooms to increase accessibility and updating lighting in classrooms and hallways.

Both Smith Elementary and Harman School will get new boilers, updated bathrooms and roof repairs.

All of the buildings will remain closed to the public through Aug. 1 to allow work to continue.

To see the complete scope of work, visit the Oakwood Schools website at https://www.oakwoodschools.org/mfp/new-mfp

Starting Wednesday, June 17, we will begin a new segment, called Work Wednesday, bringing you more details of Phase 1.

post_text:
What are you reading?

"I'm almost always reading & listening to multiple books at a time. I try to stay current and am constantly previewing for LRL in children's literature. I also love to read adult historical fiction and try to choose several summer picks from Modern Mrs. Darcy's blog. Currently, I'm reading Here in the Real World by Sara Pennypacker and Tree of Dreams by Laura Resau in children's lit and listening to This Tender Land by William Kent Krueger in adult fiction," Harman Media Specialist Holly Ford.

Oakwood Schools is saying goodbye to two long-term staff members who help keep things moving along in the right direction.

Van driver Bill Meyer is retiring from the District. Meyer, a graduate of Centerville High School, began working for Oakwood Schools in 1998, after a 35-year career in the banking industry.

Bill lives in Oakwood with his wife Donna. The schools are quite the family affair for Meyer. He has two daughters and a son in law who have worked in the District.

Also retiring is van driver Scott Nelson. Nelson began working for the District in 1999 after working in the trucking industry for 20 years. Nelson is a graduate of the Greenbrier Military School in West Virginia and Ohio University, where he earned his bachelors of science in journalism. Go Bobcats! Scott lives in Centerville with his wife Mary Lou.

Best of luck to Bill and Scott, you will be missed.

Citing her “unwavering devotion,” and encouraging nature, the nominations for this year’s Oakwood Schools Foundation Parker Love of Teaching and Lifelong Learning Award winner describe an educator who makes a difference in her students’ lives.

This year’s winner is Family and Consumer Science teacher Leslie Blythe. Blythe becomes the 10th winner of the award established to honor a current Oakwood teacher who uniquely inspires the full potential of each student with whom he or she works.

“Mrs. Blythe is a role model to me. Her unwavering devotion to the school and all the people in it is so amazing. I truly hope that in the future, I will be able to have such a positive impact on another person’s life as she had on mine,” wrote one student in a nominating letter.

One student summed up the impact Blythe has on her students saying, “Mrs. Blythe will forever continue to share her encouragement with students just like me.”

To learn more about the award and the The Oakwood Schools Foundation visit their website at https://www.oakwoodschools.org/community/osf

Congratulations Leslie!

post_text:
We are sorry.

We regret recycling books, recently found in a storage area in one of our buildings, without first making a better attempt to repurpose the texts.

The books were recently discovered when we were clearing out a storage area that had gone untouched for approximately 15 years. When our staff found the books, they contacted our book vendor who did come to review what was found. He was able to only use a few of the books, indicating many were out of date, water damaged or otherwise beyond repair. We know we then should have attempted to contact other groups to see if there was an interest in the books. We also should have offered the books to our community members. Again, we apologize for not taking these additional steps first.

We have removed the books from the recycling bin and moved them inside our building. Due to today’s weather, we do not want to leave the books outside. We will make them available to anyone who would like to pick them up. Please contact Traci Hale, Community Relations Director, at hale.traci@oakwoodschools.org to make those arrangements.

post_text:
Students around Oakwood and the country are hitting the books hard as they head into AP testing season.

Before the students in French 5 AP moved into off-site instruction, the class was studying the AP Theme of Beauty and Aesthetics.

Part of this unit discussed culinary beauty, and more specifically, plating. So after two days of reading, discussing and watching French chef videos, students put their knowledge to the test.

The results were magnifique et délicieux!

post_text: The AcaDec Flower sale is back! This Wednesday, May 6 from 4-6 p.m. you can buy a beautiful hanging basket from Bern's Garden Center and support the defending National Champion Academic Decathlon team. There will be a mix of baskets available including Red dragon wing begonias for $25 and the Bern’s select mix for $30 in a variety of colors. Pull into a parking spot at Mack Hummon Stadium and volunteers, in masks and gloves, will collect payment and deliver a plant to your car. Thank you for your support of OHS Academic Decathlon!

post_text:
Seven educators have been nominated for the Oakwood Schools 2020 Sam Andrews Educational Hall of Honor.

The nominees are:
Deborah Anderson, Elementary Music Teacher, 1988-2011
Janet Block, Kindergarten Teacher, 1996-2014
Nance Bradds, Principal, 1999-2012
Catherine (Cathy) Fain, Teacher/Gifted Coordinator, 1991-2009
Randy Neff, Math Teacher, Coach, Junior High Athletic Director, 1999-2018
Charlotte Seitner, 3rd Grade Teacher, 1941-1962
Douglas Schivley, History Teacher, Guidance Counselor, Coach, 1980-2005

You are invited to provide letters of support on behalf of these educators. Letters should be submitted no later than May 20 to Dr. Kyle Ramey, Superintendent, Oakwood Board of Education, 20 Rubicon Road, Dayton, Ohio 45409, or via email at ramey.kyle@oakwoodschools.org.

For more information on the Sam Andrews Educational Hall of Honor, visit the Oakwood Schools website at https://www.oakwoodschools.org/community/sam-andrews

post_text: A big Oakwood Schools welcome to the newest member of the Oakwood Schools Foundation team Brandy McFall.
shared_text:
The Oakwood Schools Foundation
April 22 at 8:38 PM ·

The Oakwood Schools Foundation is pleased to introduce Brandy McFall as the team's Development Director.

McFall has spent the majority of her career in local non-profit fundraising and comes to OSF most recently from the Dayton Art Institute, where she served as Senior Sponsorship Officer and Development Director during her tenure.

Prior to the DAI, McFall was the Director of Development for Foundation Relations at the University of Dayton. McFall brings with her extensive experience in a variety of types of education fundraising from her time at UD, as well as fundraising for high-quality art education programming and mission-based initiatives at the DAI. McFall has also worked with…
